S.Q,F.C. and experimental site
F.C.,J.C
At 10-12 MeV - the Variable Energy
Compact CV28 Cyclotron,Institut FOR Chemistry,Yulich
At 14.5MeV - MGC-20 in Debrecen
Quasi-monoenergetic neutrons of energy between
8.7 MeV and 10.7 MeV were produced by bombarding a
deuterium gas target with deuterons of Energy between
6 and 8 MeV.
The average neutron energy effective at the sample was
calculated using a Monte Carlo program.
The neutron flux densities in front and at the back of
the sample were determined via the Al-27(n,alpha)
monitor reaction whose cross section was taken from
the literature. The average neutron flux density
effective at the sample was then obtained taking into
account the flux distribution inside the sample. The
relative flux distribution inside the sample was
calculated both by Monte Carlo and numerical integrat.
techniques. The calculated flux distribution was
finally normalised to the value from the front of
the Al monitor foil and the resulting absolute
distribution was averaged. Each flux density was
weighted with respect to its irradiation time.
Al monitor foils of 200 micro-m thickness were attached
at the front and at the back of the tube. Each sample
was irradiated several times, each time with a fresh
Al monitor. Each sample was irradiated at
zero degree direction for between 7 to 10 hrs and 10
to 20 hrs, respectively. Measurements were carried out
several months after irradiations and took about 3
days for each sample.
The neutron activation technique was used.
140 cm3 3 HPGe detector.
The gamma activity of the irradiated samples
was measured using a Ge(Li) detector.
Also, it used for measurement the radioactivity of the
monitor reaction product (24Na). The peak area
analysis was done using the program Maestro. Due to
the large dimensions of the sample, the inhomogeneous
distribution of the activity and the low count rates,
the detection efficiency was determined following a
procedure which makes use of counting in various
geometry arrangements gamma-rays from a standard
source and from the samples. Self-absorption
was measured by placing an unirradiated absorbent
of material and geometry similar to the those of the
samples between the source and the detector.
The monitor cross
sections were taken from IRDF,1990.
The activity of the monitor product was corrected
for background contributions. The correction due to
breakup of deuterons on D2 gas was negligible.
Corrections for background neutrons and for coinciden-
ce were applied. The latter was estimated from the
decay scheme and the effective detector efficiency.
Total uncertainty. Principal sources are:
Uncertainty in sample weight
Uncertainty of irradiation time
Uncertainty in irradiation geometry and beam
deviation
Uncertainty in correction for activity
induced by background neutrons (gas in/out, breakup)
Error in excitation function of monitor
reaction
The error the averaging of neutron flux
Error in peak area analysis
Error in statistics of gamma counting
Uncertainty in the efficiency of the detector
Uncertainty in the decay-data
